= Seeking Help (Isti‘ānah), Relief (Istighāthah), and Refuge (Isti‘ādhah)

*Meanings:*

 _Isti‘ānah_: Seeking help or assistance.
 
 _Istighāthah_: Seeking rescue or relief, especially in hardship.
 
_Isti‘ādhah_: Seeking protection or refuge
 

*Evidence That These Are Acts of Worship:*


Isti‘ānah (Seeking Help):

Allāh says:#quran-block[إِيَّاكَ نَعۡبُدُ وَإِيَّاكَ نَسۡتَعِينُ ٥
][You alone we worship, and You alone we ask for help.
(Al-Fātiḥah
 Q1:5)]



Istighāthah (Seeking Relief):

Allāh says:#quran-block[إِذۡ تَسۡتَغِيثُونَ رَبَّكُمۡ فَٱسۡتَجَابَ لَكُمۡ أَنِّي مُمِدُّكُم بِأَلۡفٖ مِّنَ ٱلۡمَلَٰٓئِكَةِ مُرۡدِفِينَ ٩
][Remember when you sought help from your Lord, and He responded to you
(Al-Anfāl
 Q8:9)
]
Isti‘ādhah (Seeking protection or refuge):

Allāh says:#quran-block[قُلۡ أَعُوذُ بِرَبِّ ٱلنَّاسِ ١
][Say: I seek refuge with the Lord of mankind.
(An-Nās Q114:1)]



*Ruling on Seeking Help, Relief, and Refuge from Other than Allāh:*

It is divided into two types:



*1. Permissible:*

When four conditions are fulfilled:

A. Two of the conditions relate to the requested thing:
 1. It must not be something exclusive to Allāh (like creating, forgiving sins, etc.).
 2. The person being asked must be able to fulfill the requirement.

B. Two conditions relate to the person being asked for help, relief, or protection:
3. The person must be alive.
4. The person must be present.


*2. Shirk (Polytheism):*

If any of the above four conditions is not met, then the act becomes Shirk (associating partners with Allāh).